mphatically against blurbs penned by friendly fellow-writers. I have been often asked to contribute quotable lines and have always refused, and of course I cannot make an exception in this case. Incidentally, my latest books are as free of these ornaments as were my very first ones.

Yours very cordially,

Vladimir Nabokov





TO: GEORGE WEIDENFELD

CC, 1 p.





Montreux, Switzerland

March 30, 1963

